Sometimes there are profitable trades, but not that often. Sometimes someon=
e is looking to sell=C2=A0100 widgets=C2=A0at $20 on the American Widget Ex=
change, and someone else is looking=C2=A0to buy 100 widgets for $21 on the =
National Widget Exchange. And so you=C2=A0can buy on the AWE and sell on th=
e NWE and make an instant $100 profit. But only=C2=A0one=C2=A0person can do=
 that. Once you buy on the AWE and sell=C2=A0on the NWE, the window is clos=
ed.
Who gets to do the trade? The most intuitive answer, in most cases, is =E2=
=80=9Cwhoever does it first.=E2=80=9D If you see the same thing trading for=
 two different prices on two different exchanges, and I don=E2=80=99t, and =
you send in the orders to the exchanges before me, then you do the trade an=
d I don=E2=80=99t. For most human-scale trades, this makes sense and is eas=
y to administer and feels basically fair.
The US stock market mostly does not operate at human time scales, and there=
 these intuitions break down. In the stock market, often, one algorithm spo=
ts=C2=A0trade opportunities a microsecond before another algorithm, and peo=
ple get mad about that. They worry that this microsecond-scale competition =
between algorithms is socially wasteful, and they worry that it is unfair t=
o people with worse algorithms. They think =E2=80=9Cyes, fine, the first pe=
rson to see a trade should get to do it,=C2=A0within reason, but there=E2=
=80=99s no social benefit to slicing it that fine.=E2=80=9D They propose th=
ings like =E2=80=9Cfrequent batch auctions,=E2=80=9D where everyone who see=
s the same trade within (say) a second of each other gets to compete on pri=
ce=C2=A0to do it, rather than competing on=C2=A0time=C2=A0down to the micro=
second.=C2=A0
Crypto, however, has a different problem. Time in electronic stock markets =
is maybe=C2=A0too continuous; the timeline of a stock exchange can be slice=
d much more finely than the human brain can comprehend. But time in crypto =
is oddly discrete. Time in crypto is measured in=C2=A0blocks. Intuitively, =
people submit=C2=A0orders to do transactions on a crypto blockchain, and th=
en periodically a batch of those transactions is=C2=A0enshrined in the offi=
cial ledger of that blockchain. In Bitcoin, a block contains roughly 10 min=
utes=E2=80=99 worth of transactions; in Ethereum, it=E2=80=99s seconds.
So intuitively, Ethereum transactions happen in big simultaneous bunches ev=
ery 12 seconds. But the bunches can=E2=80=99t really be simultaneous: If th=
ere is one rare nonfungible token for sale, and two people want to buy it, =
only one of them can. One transaction has to be first. So the transactions =
within a block are=C2=A0ordered; they happen in sequence. But they are not =
necessarily ordered by=C2=A0time.
How does the blockchain decide which transactions to record, and in what or=
der? In Ethereum, the answer is: with money.=C2=A0People who want to do tra=
nsactions on the Ethereum network pay fees to execute the transactions; the=
re is a flat base fee, but people can also bid more =E2=80=94=C2=A0a =E2=80=
=9Cpriority fee=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Ctip=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0to get the=
ir transactions executed quickly. Every 12 seconds, some computer on the Et=
hereum network is selected to record the transactions in a block. This comp=
uter used to be called a =E2=80=9Cminer,=E2=80=9D but in current proof-of-s=
take Ethereum blocks are recorded by computers called =E2=80=9Cvalidators.=
=E2=80=9D Each block is compiled by one validator, selected more or less at=
 random, called a =E2=80=9Cproposer=E2=80=9D; the other validators vote to =
accept the block. The validators share the transaction fees, with the block=
 proposer getting more than the other validators.
The block proposer will naturally prioritize the transactions that pay more=
 fees, because then it will get more money. And, again, the validators are =
all computers; they will be programmed=C2=A0to select the transactions that=
 pay them the most money. And in fact there is a division of labor in moder=
n Ethereum, where a computer called a =E2=80=9Cblock builder=E2=80=9D puts =
together a list of transactions that will pay the most money to the validat=
ors, and then the block proposer proposes a block with that list so it can =
get paid.
And so if you see 100 widget tokens trading for $20 on one Ethereum decentr=
alized exchange, and 100 widget tokens trading for $21 on another Ethereum =
decentralized exchange, you can buy them at $20 each and sell them for $21 =
each and make $100. But if I=C2=A0also=C2=A0see that arbitrage, I will=C2=
=A0also=C2=A0put in those orders. Which of our trades will execute first? W=
hoever pays more in execution fees. How much should I offer to pay? Oh, you=
 know, it=E2=80=99s a competitive auction. So roughly $99. The validators s=
hould get most of the money from the arbitrage. This is called =E2=80=9CMEV=
,=E2=80=9D for =E2=80=9Cminer extractable value,=E2=80=9D though now Ethere=
um doesn=E2=80=99t have miners and the acronym stands much less informative=
ly for =E2=80=9Cmaximal extractable value.=E2=80=9D
What are the chances that both of us discovered the same arbitrage within 1=
2 seconds of each other? Well, pretty good, in a competitive market with a =
lot of arbitrageurs. But also, traditionally, when we want=C2=A0to do these=
 transactions, we submit=C2=A0our orders=C2=A0publicly=C2=A0to the Ethereum=
 network. (To the =E2=80=9Cmempool,=E2=80=9D the name given to the place wh=
ere orders reside before they are included in a block.) Everyone can see th=
e mempool. So if you are a clever speedy arbitrageur, watching a bunch of d=
ecentralized exchanges for mispricings, you might see a=C2=A0mispricing and=
 submit=C2=A0your arbitrage orders. And if=C2=A0I am a clever speedy=C2=A0f=
ront-runner, watching the mempool for arbitrage trades, I would submit the =
same trades a second or two after you, and pay more to execute them. And th=
en I=C2=A0get to do the arbitrage and you don=E2=80=99t.
But if I am a clever speedy front-runner, I don=E2=80=99t even have to wait=
 for arbitrage trades. Let=E2=80=99s say you are not a clever arbitrageur, =
but just a person who really likes the Shiba Inu token on the Ethereum bloc=
kchain. You submit a huge order to buy SHIB on a decentralized exchange. Th=
at will, quite predictably, push up the price of SHIB.
  [1]
=C2=A0If I see that order, I can just jump ahead of it: I can pay a bit mor=
e in transaction fees to get my trades to execute first, and then I can buy=
 the SHIB tokens ahead of you and then=C2=A0sell=C2=A0them to you for a pro=
fit, all within the same block.
That seems kind of rough on you? This sort of trade is sometimes called a =
=E2=80=9Csandwich attack=E2=80=9D: I see your order to buy SHIB, and I sand=
wich it between my order to buy SHIB (before you do, at a lower price) and =
my order to sell SHIB (after you do, at a higher price). And people talk ab=
out =E2=80=9Cgeneralized front running=E2=80=9D as a strategy:
A generalized front-runner bot=C2=A0will search the mempool for profitable =
transactions, then copy the transaction and replace the sender address with=
 their own, then increase their bid (gas price) to price + x to be included=
 in a block first front running the original searcher.
I am giving a simplistic and somewhat old-fashioned description of MEV, and=
 modern Ethereum has a whole, like, institutional structure around it. Ther=
e are private mempools, where you can hide transactions from bots. There is=
 Flashbots, =E2=80=9Ca research and development organization formed to miti=
gate the negative externalities posed by Maximal Extractable Value (MEV) to=
 stateful blockchains, starting with Ethereum,=E2=80=9D which has things li=
ke MEV-Boost, which creates =E2=80=9Ca competitive block-building market=E2=
=80=9D where validators can =E2=80=9Cmaximize their staking reward by selli=
ng their blockspace to an open market,=E2=80=9D and MEV-Share, =E2=80=9Can =
open-source protocol for users, wallets, and applications to internalize th=
e MEV that their transactions create,=E2=80=9D letting them =E2=80=9Cselect=
ively share data about their transactions with searchers who bid to include=
 the transactions in bundles=E2=80=9D and get paid.=C2=A0
Basically, transaction data on Ethereum is informative, and the value of th=
at information (in making profitable trades) is quantifiable, and=C2=A0ther=
e are cutthroat auctions among people who want to use that data to make the=
ir own trades, and the people doing the transactions that create the data c=
an themselves get paid for their data.=C2=A0
There is a sort of cool purity to this. In stock markets, some people are f=
aster than others, and can make money by trading ahead of a big order,
  [2]
=C2=A0and people get mad about this and think it is unfair and propose solu=
tions. And when money changes hands for speed advantages =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9Cpayment for order flow,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Ccolocation=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0people complain about corruption. In crypto it=E2=80=99s like =E2=
=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s create an efficient market in trading ahead of big orde=
rs.=E2=80=9D I once wrote: =E2=80=9CRather than solve this concern about tr=
aditional markets, crypto made it explicit.=E2=80=9D That feels almost like=
 a general philosophy of crypto: Take the problems of traditional finance a=
nd make them,=C2=A0worse, sure, but more transparent and visible and explic=
it and subject to unbridled free markets.
In traditional financial markets, people sometimes get in trouble for =E2=
=80=9Cspoofing,=E2=80=9D for submitting trade orders designed to fool peopl=
e (algorithms) about their true trading intent. Every so often,=C2=A0the sp=
oofer=E2=80=99s defense will be =E2=80=9Cno, all these algorithms are tryin=
g to front-run me, they are trying to use my order information to make mone=
y by trading ahead of me. So I created fake order information to fool them.=
 I=E2=80=99m the hero in this story; the bots trying to front-run me are th=
e villains.=E2=80=9D This tends not to work.
Here, maybe, is the crypto version of that.=C2=A0Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Ava Be=
nny-Morrison reports:

