Crudely speaking there are two sorts of crypto tokens. There are=C2=A0fungi=
ble=C2=A0tokens, like Bitcoin and Ether and Tether and Solana, which have a=
pproximately cash-like properties: If a thing costs two=C2=A0Bitcoins, it d=
oesn=E2=80=99t matter=C2=A0which two Bitcoins you use to pay for it; any tw=
o Bitcoins are just as good as any other two Bitcoins. And there are=C2=A0n=
onfungible=C2=A0tokens, NFTs, like Bored Ape Yacht Club, which have approxi=
mately art-object-like properties: Each Bored Ape is different, and some =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0based on their rarity or aesthetics or provenance =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0are worth much more than others.
Intuitively, fungible tokens are indistinguishable coins, while NFTs are un=
ique images. But=C2=A0really=C2=A0neither of those things is true.=C2=A0Rea=
lly they are both entries in detailed permanent transaction ledgers. An NFT=
, for example,=C2=A0isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0the little drawing of the monkey; th=
e NFT is simply a numbered entry in a ledger that points to the drawing of =
the monkey. I once wrote that =E2=80=9Can NFT consists of a series of numbe=
red tokens, and the thing that makes it an NFT is that it has a different n=
umber in its tokenId field from the other tokens in its series.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0
Meanwhile a fungible token like Bitcoin is=C2=A0not=C2=A0a numbered entry i=
n a ledger; there is such a thing as =E2=80=9CBored Ape Number 3=E2=80=9D b=
ut there is no such thing as =E2=80=9CBitcoin Number 3.=E2=80=9D But there =
is a permanent immutable computer ledger containing every Bitcoin transacti=
on, which means that you=C2=A0could, sort of, trace the ledger back to find=
 what the third Bitcoin was and who holds it now.
  [7]

More generally, you could, if you wanted to, treat Bitcoins as completely n=
onfungible. You could trace back the history of any Bitcoin, or fraction of=
 a Bitcoin. And then you could say things like:
=09=E2=80=9CI am willing to pay more for old=C2=A0Bitcoins, ones that were =
mined in like 2009, than I will for new Bitcoins, ones that were only mined=
 in 2024.=E2=80=9D=09=E2=80=9CI am willing to pay more for Bitcoins with co=
ol provenance, like ones that were once owned by Satoshi Nakamoto=C2=A0or u=
sed to pay for the 2010 Bitcoin Pizza, than I will for regular old Bitcoins=
 with no fun history.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=09=E2=80=9CI am willing to pay=C2=A0le=
ss=C2=A0for Bitcoins with a troubled regulatory history, like the ones that=
 were stolen in the Bitfinex hack, than I will for Bitcoins with a clean re=
gulatory history.=E2=80=9D

Bitcoins are fungible simply because it is standard convention among Bitcoi=
n users to=C2=A0treat=C2=A0them as fungible, but they are=C2=A0distinguisha=
ble from one another, and if=C2=A0you wanted to discriminate among Bitcoins=
 you=C2=A0could. People mostly don=E2=80=99t, but the last thing on that li=
st =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Ctry not to accept=C2=A0Bitcoins that have been s=
tolen or are otherwise of interest to US law enforcement=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0does=C2=A0have some traction. Some Bitcoins really=C2=A0are=C2=A0less=
 valuable than others.
And some are more. Here is a delightful story from Joel Khalili at Wired:
In the same way a dollar is made up of 100 cents, one bitcoin is composed o=
f 100 million satoshis=E2=80=94or sats, for short. But not all sats are mad=
e equal. Those produced in the year bitcoin was created are considered vint=
