<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sometimes there are profitable trades, but not=
 that often. Sometimes someone is looking to sell=C2=A0100 widgets=C2=A0at =
$20 on the American Widget Exchange, and someone else is looking=C2=A0to bu=
y 100 widgets for $21 on the National Widget Exchange. And so you=C2=A0can =
buy on the AWE and sell on the NWE and make an instant $100 profit. But onl=
y=C2=A0<em>one=C2=A0</em>person can do that. Once you buy on the AWE and se=
ll=C2=A0on the NWE, the window is closed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Who gets to do the trade? The most intuitive a=
nswer, in most cases, is =E2=80=9Cwhoever does it first.=E2=80=9D If you se=
e the same thing trading for two different prices on two different exchange=
s, and I don=E2=80=99t, and you send in the orders to the exchanges before =
me, then you do the trade and I don=E2=80=99t. For most human-scale trades,=
 this makes sense and is easy to administer and feels basically fair.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The US stock market mostly does not operate at=
 human time scales, and there <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/35403556.256337/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS92aWV3L2FydGl=
jbGVzLzIwMTgtMDctMDIvd2FsbC1zdHJlZXQtaXMtc2hhcnBlbmluZy1vdXItbmFub3NlY29uZH=
M_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUxNjI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlP=
W5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNTE2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB918bb945" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">these intuitions break down</a>. In the=
 stock market, often, one algorithm spots=C2=A0trade opportunities a micros=
econd before another algorithm, and people get mad about that. They worry t=
hat this microsecond-scale competition between algorithms is socially waste=
ful, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35403556.=
256337/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvRmxhc2hfQm95cw/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB9bc748e5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">they worry</a> that it is unfair to people wi=
th worse algorithms. They think =E2=80=9Cyes, fine, the first person to see=
 a trade should get to do it,=C2=A0<em>within reason</em>, but there=E2=80=
=99s no social benefit to slicing it that fine.=E2=80=9D They propose thing=
s like =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35=
403556.256337/aHR0cHM6Ly9hY2FkZW1pYy5vdXAuY29tL3FqZS9hcnRpY2xlLzEzMC80LzE1N=
DcvMTkxNjE0Ng/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc0ceb6b3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">frequent batch auc=
tions</a>,=E2=80=9D where everyone who sees the same trade within (say) a s=
econd of each other gets to compete <em>on price</em>=C2=A0to do it, rather=
 than competing on=C2=A0<em>time=C2=A0</em>down to the microsecond.=C2=A0</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Crypto, however, has a different problem. Time=
 in electronic stock markets is maybe=C2=A0<em>too </em>continuous; the tim=
eline of a stock exchange can be sliced much more finely than the human bra=
in can comprehend. But time in crypto is oddly discrete. Time in crypto is =
measured in=C2=A0<em>blocks</em>. Intuitively, people submit=C2=A0orders to=
 do transactions on a crypto blockchain, and then periodically a batch of t=
hose transactions is=C2=A0enshrined in the official ledger of that blockcha=
in. In <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35403556.25=
6337/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvY2tjaGFpbi5jb20vZXhwbG9yZXI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cBeb22cd1b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">Bitcoin</a>, a block contains roughly 10 minutes=E2=80=
=99 worth of transactions; in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/35403556.256337/aHR0cHM6Ly9ldGhlcmV1bS5vcmcvZW4vZGV2ZWxvcGVycy9=
kb2NzL2Jsb2Nrcy8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4db56ff5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Ethereum</a>, i=
t=E2=80=99s seconds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So intuitively, Ethereum transactions happen i=
n big simultaneous bunches every 12 seconds. But the bunches can=E2=80=99t =
really be simultaneous: If there is one rare nonfungible token for sale, an=
d two people want to buy it, only one of them can. One transaction has to b=
e first. So the transactions within a block are=C2=A0<em>ordered</em>; they=
 happen in sequence. But they are not necessarily ordered by=C2=A0<em>time.=
</em></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How does the blockchain decide which transacti=
ons to record, and in what order? In Ethereum, the answer is: with money.=
=C2=A0People who want to do transactions on the Ethereum network <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35403556.256337/aHR0cHM6Ly9l=
dGhlcmV1bS5vcmcvZW4vZGV2ZWxvcGVycy9kb2NzL2dhcy8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBec=
411f8c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">pay fees to execute the transactions</a>; there is a flat b=
ase fee, but people can also bid more =E2=80=94=C2=A0a =E2=80=9Cpriority fe=
e=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Ctip=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0to get their transaction=
s executed quickly. Every 12 seconds, some computer on the Ethereum network=
 is selected to record the transactions in a block. This computer used to b=
e called a =E2=80=9Cminer,=E2=80=9D but in current proof-of-stake Ethereum =
blocks are recorded by computers called =E2=80=9Cvalidators.=E2=80=9D Each =
block is compiled by one validator, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/35403556.256337/aHR0cHM6Ly9ldGhlcmV1bS5vcmcvZW4vZGV2ZWxvc=
GVycy9kb2NzL2NvbnNlbnN1cy1tZWNoYW5pc21zL3Bvcy9ibG9jay1wcm9wb3NhbC8/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB46a07f6a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">selected</a> more or less at random, cal=
led a =E2=80=9Cproposer=E2=80=9D; the other validators vote to accept the b=
lock. The validators <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/35403556.256337/aHR0cHM6Ly9ldGhlcmV1bS5vcmcvZW4vZGV2ZWxvcGVycy9kb2NzL2Nv=
bnNlbnN1cy1tZWNoYW5pc21zL3Bvcy9yZXdhcmRzLWFuZC1wZW5hbHRpZXMv/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cB22da7fd1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">share the transaction fees</a>, with the bloc=
k proposer getting more than the other validators.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The block proposer will naturally prioritize t=
he transactions that pay more fees, because then it will get more money. An=
d, again, the validators are all computers; they will be <em>programmed=C2=
=A0</em>to select the transactions that pay them the most money. And in fac=
t there is a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35403=
556.256337/aHR0cHM6Ly9ldGhyZXNlYXIuY2gvdC9wcm9wb3Nlci1ibG9jay1idWlsZGVyLXNl=
