<span>[3]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">That is, they front-ran and spoof=
ed the front-runners: They put in a big order saying =E2=80=9Cbuy a ton of =
[some nonsense tokens],=E2=80=9D front-running bots said =E2=80=9Cooh, big =
bid for nonsense tokens, let=E2=80=99s get ahead of that,=E2=80=9D and the =
front-running bots bought the nonsense tokens ahead of them. But then they =
tampered with the transactions to replace their own buy order with a <em>se=
ll </em>order,=C2=A0<em>selling=C2=A0</em>the nonsense tokens =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0effectively, <em>to=C2=A0</em>the front-runners =E2=80=94 at inflated pr=
ices for $25 million. =E2=80=9CIn effect, the Tampered Transactions drained=
 the particular liquidity pools of all the cryptocurrency that the Victim T=
raders had deposited based on their frontrun trades.=E2=80=9D</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now. Is this =E2=80=A6=C2=A0bad? Sure, I guess=
. In Step 5, the Peraire-Buenos do seem to have exploited a real vulnerabil=
ity in how Ethereum=E2=80=99s consensus mechanism worked. I do not pretend =
to fully understand the technical details, but here is a <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35403556.256337/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb2xsZWN0=
aXZlLmZsYXNoYm90cy5uZXQvdC9wb3N0LW1vcnRlbS1hcHJpbC0zcmQtMjAyMy1tZXYtYm9vc3Q=
tcmVsYXktaW5jaWRlbnQtYW5kLXJlbGF0ZWQtdGltaW5nLWlzc3VlLzE1NDA/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cB894e41fb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">Flashbots postmortem</a> of the exploit. (The=
y sent a signed but invalid block header to the relay, which caused the rel=
ay to publish=C2=A0the contents of the proposed block, which they used to c=
onstruct their own block exploiting those contents as the proposer of the b=
lock.) The Justice Department calls it =E2=80=9Can alleged=C2=A0novel schem=
e by the defendants to exploit the very integrity of the Ethereum blockchai=
n,=E2=80=9D and that seems right: If people can reach in to alter the order=
 of transactions to swipe $25 million, that does sort of undermine the inte=
grity of the blockchain.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also they did some bad googling. Before they d=
id the trade, Anton Peraire-Bueno allegedly =E2=80=9Csearched online for cr=
yptocurrency exchanges with limited =E2=80=98know your customer=E2=80=99 pr=
otocols and ways to launder cryptocurrency, including searches for =E2=80=
=98how to wash crypto=E2=80=99 and =E2=80=98cefi exchanges with no kyc.=E2=
=80=99=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgrou=
nd-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> And after the trade, as they were allegedly =E2=80=9Claundering the fr=
aud proceeds from the Exploit,=E2=80=9D James Peraire-Bueno allegedly =E2=
=80=9Csearched online for, among other things, =E2=80=98money laundering,=
=E2=80=99 =E2=80=98exploit,=E2=80=99 =E2=80=98computer fraud abuse act,=E2=
=80=99<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color:=
 transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> and =E2=80=98does the united states extradite to [foreign country].=E2=
=80=99=E2=80=9D The Justice Department, reasonably, cites these searches as=
 evidence of a guilty conscience. Also though I wonder how well they worked=
? Like, has anyone ever (1) acquired $25 million of ill-gotten money, (2) g=
oogled =E2=80=9Cmoney laundering=E2=80=9D and (3) successfully used to resu=
lts to launder the money? On the other hand I bet googling =E2=80=9Ccefi ex=
changes with no kyc=E2=80=9D works great; really exchanges should pay a lot=
 for those keywords.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But to me what is wild about this case is that=
 the Justice Department is bringing down the full weight of US federal crim=
inal law to protect <em>Ethereum front-running bots</em>. The word =E2=80=
=9Cfront-run=E2=80=9D is right there in the indictment! The Justice Departm=
ent has a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35403556=
.256337/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3YvdXNhby1lZG55L3ByL2Zvcm1lci1nbG9iYWw=
taGVhZC1oc2JjLXMtZm9yZWlnbi1leGNoYW5nZS1jYXNoLXRyYWRpbmctZm91bmQtZ3VpbHR5LW=
9yY2hlc3RyYXRpbmc/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3c69c1eb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">long</a>=C2=A0=
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35403556.256337/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3YvdXNhby1zZG55L3ByL2Zvcm1lci1hbmFseXN0LWNoYXJnZ=
WQtOC1taWxsaW9uLWluc2lkZXItdHJhZGluZy1zY2hlbWUtZnJvbnQtcnVubmluZy1lbXBsb3ll=
ci1z/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1cfb9bc8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">history</a> of <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35403556.256337/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuanVzdGljZS5nb3YvdXNhby1zZG55L3ByL3RyYWRlci1sYXJnZS1jYW5hZGlhbi1hc3NldC1tY=
W5hZ2VtZW50LWZpcm0tY2hhcmdlZC1pbnNpZGVyLXRyYWRpbmctZW5nYWdpbmc/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB6d7cb136" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">prosecuting</a> people for front-running! Be=
cause it is traditionally a crime! In traditional finance, =E2=80=9Cfront-r=
unning=E2=80=9D is understood to mean violating a fiduciary duty to your cu=
stomers (or employer, etc.) by trading ahead of their orders, and it is=C2=
=A0a crime.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-c=
olor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But here the Justice Department is protecting =
the front-runners. And the trades that the Victim Traders were trying to do=
 look, to the naked eye, bad? They were =E2=80=9Cwe see you are trying to b=
uy this illiquid cryptocurrency, so we=E2=80=99re going to buy it ahead of =
you so we can rip you off.=E2=80=9D In Ethereum, that is pretty normal, and=
 there is a large institutional structure to make it work in a predictable =
and fair-ish way. But in traditional markets it just seems bad.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have talked a few times <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35403556.256337/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDQtMDkvYS1tZW1lLXN0b2NrLWZvci1w=
cml2YXRlLWNvbXBhbmllcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTE2MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWV=
tYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA1MTYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW=
1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB875f826a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">about Avi Eisenber=
g</a>, the crypto trader arrested (and convicted) for fraud because he did =
some market manipulation on a decentralized crypto exchange. He absolutely =
did do that manipulation, but his defense =E2=80=94=C2=A0which did not work=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0was that the crypto exchange did not have any norms=C2=A0<e=
m>against=C2=A0</em>it. What he did was allowed by the exchange=E2=80=99s c=
ode, he argued, so it was allowed. External norms like =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=
=99t do market manipulation=E2=80=9D did not apply.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is controversial, and a lot of people in =
and out of crypto have complaints of the form =E2=80=9Clook, if decentraliz=
ed finance exchanges do not want to be subject to US regulation, why does t=
he federal government need to protect them from market manipulators?=E2=80=
=9D I am sympathetic to those complaints.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But here! I mean! Ethereum and its decentraliz=
ed exchanges have a market structure that is like =E2=80=9Cbots can look at=
 your transactions and front-run them if that=E2=80=99s profitable.=E2=80=
=9D And these guys, allegedly, front-ran the front-runners; they turned the=
 market structure around so that=C2=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em>could get an early=
 look at the front-running bots=E2=80=99 front-running transactions and fro=
nt-run them instead. By=C2=A0hacking, sure, sure, it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0bad. Bu=
t it leaves the Justice Department in the odd position of saying that the i=
ntegrity of crypto front-running is important and must be defended.</p>
