<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Crudely speaking there are two sorts of crypto=
 tokens. There are=C2=A0<em>fungible=C2=A0</em>tokens, like Bitcoin and Eth=
er and Tether and Solana, which have approximately cash-like properties: If=
 a thing costs two=C2=A0Bitcoins, it doesn=E2=80=99t matter=C2=A0<em>which =
</em>two Bitcoins you use to pay for it; any two Bitcoins are just as good =
as any other two Bitcoins. And there are=C2=A0<em>nonfungible=C2=A0</em>tok=
ens, NFTs, like Bored Ape Yacht Club, which have approximately art-object-l=
ike properties: Each Bored Ape is different, and some =E2=80=94=C2=A0based =
on their rarity or aesthetics or provenance =E2=80=94=C2=A0are worth much m=
ore than others.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Intuitively, fungible tokens are indistinguish=
able coins, while NFTs are unique images. But=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0</em>nei=
ther of those things is true.=C2=A0Really they are both entries in detailed=
 permanent transaction ledgers. An NFT, for example,=C2=A0<em>isn=E2=80=99t=
=C2=A0</em>the little drawing of the monkey; the NFT is simply a numbered e=
ntry in a ledger that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/35403556.256337/aHR0cHM6Ly9tb3hpZS5vcmcvMjAyMi8wMS8wNy93ZWIzLWZpcnN0LWl=
tcHJlc3Npb25zLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1948adb4" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">points to t=
he drawing of the monkey</a>. I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/35403556.256337/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9mZWF0dXJlc=
y8yMDIyLXRoZS1jcnlwdG8tc3RvcnkvP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MTYyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9t=
ZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDUxNiZ1dG1fY2F=
tcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd433bed0" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">once wro=
te</a> that =E2=80=9Can NFT consists of a series of numbered tokens, and th=
e thing that makes it an NFT is that it has a different number in its token=
Id field from the other tokens in its series.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile a fungible token like Bitcoin is=C2=
=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>a <em>numbered</em> entry in a ledger; there is <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35403556.256337/aHR0cHM6=
Ly9vcGVuc2VhLmlvL2Fzc2V0cy9ldGhlcmV1bS8weGJjNGNhMGVkYTc2NDdhOGFiN2MyMDYxYzJ=
lMTE4YTE4YTkzNmYxM2QvMw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdefb7d69" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">such a t=
hing as</a> =E2=80=9CBored Ape Number 3=E2=80=9D but there is no such thing=
 as =E2=80=9CBitcoin Number 3.=E2=80=9D But there is a permanent immutable =
computer ledger containing every Bitcoin transaction, which means that you=
=C2=A0<em>could</em>, sort of, trace the ledger back to find what the third=
 Bitcoin was and who holds it now.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foot=
note-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !=
important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;=
">
<span>[7]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More generally, you could, if you wanted to, t=
reat Bitcoins as completely nonfungible. You could trace back the history o=
f any Bitcoin, or fraction of a Bitcoin. And then you could say things like=
:</p>
