r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">a delightful story from Joel Khalili at Wired</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the same way a dollar is made u=
p of 100 cents, one bitcoin is composed of 100 million satoshis=E2=80=94or =
sats, for short. But not all sats are made equal. Those produced in the yea=
r bitcoin was created are considered vintage, like a fine wine. Other covet=
ed sats were part of transactions made by bitcoin=E2=80=99s inventor. Some =
correspond with a particular transaction milestone. These and various other=
 properties make some sats more scarce than others=E2=80=94and therefore mo=
re valuable. The very rarest can sell for tens of millions of times their f=
ace value; in April, a single sat, normally worth $0.0006, sold for $2.1 mi=
llion.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are two interesting points here. One is =
simply the existence of =E2=80=9Crare sats=E2=80=9D: To at least some =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0Bitcoin collectors? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0some satoshis are worth more=
 than others, due to their history or provenance.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other is that, while some Bitcoin enthusia=
sts value rare sats highly and will pay a lot for them, others just cheeril=
y assume=C2=A0that Bitcoin is a fungible currency. And so there is a trade:=
</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[Bill]=C2=A0Restey is part of a sm=
all, tight-knit band of hunters trying to root out these rare sats, which a=
re scattered across the bitcoin network. They do this by depositing batches=
 of bitcoin with a crypto exchange, then withdrawing the same amount=E2=80=
=94a little like depositing cash with a bank teller and immediately taking =
it out again from the ATM outside. The coins they receive in return are not=
 the same they deposited, giving them a fresh stash through which to sift. =
They rinse and repeat.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you deposit one Bitcoin on a crypto exchang=
e and then withdraw it, you will get one Bitcoin. But you will not get the =
same Bitcoin you put in. The exchange will say =E2=80=9Cehh Bitcoins are Bi=
tcoins, it doesn=E2=80=99t matter.=E2=80=9D But you might disagree.</p>
